Good afternoon,

I would like to validate my base mental model understanding of proofs in O1JS zkApps, namely on how to develop proofs with value and significance. Writing a Smart Contract with an `@method` does not mean writing a proof that proves anything of value. In the text that follows, I will describe my understanding regarding Zero-Knowledge proofs in genernal, and zkApps written in O1JS. 

Zero-Knowledge proof validation only returns true or false. If true is returned, that means the proof is valid, and any of the state included (committed to by the proof) in the proof is also valid. This state includes the state updates on-chain, and any return values by the @method. If false is returned, it means that the proof is invalid, and any of the state committed to by the proof cannot be verified to be valid.

My main question lies to what is actually being committed to in the proof? From what I understand, In O1JS Smart Contract @mehtods, I'm only committing to data that I do .assert*()on. If I don't do .assert*(), then I'm not really committing to much. For example, suppose I have the following method myMethod():

```
@method myMethod(number: Field): Field {
    return number.add(2);
}
```

After I compile the smart contract and generate the proof for myMethod(), am I really committing to something useful? Am I generating a useful proof? Or am I just proving that I received some private input and returned a number, without any assertions to that number? Do I actually have a guarantee that I calculated `number + 2` with number being some private input? Is the execution of the `myMethod()` code guaranteed, like on the EVM chain?

Would the following version make the proof more useful?

```
@method myMethod(number: Field): Field {
  const result = number.add(2)
  result.assertEquals(number.add(2)) 
  return result
}
```

